And I was fine. I am fine. Everything's fine. It's just a follow-up. It's nothing.

76
00:04:42,330 --> 00:04:45,069
It's a biopsy, Joe. "Biopsy" and "nothing" don't go together.

77
00:04:45,137 --> 00:04:48,520
People don't get a biopsy for the hell of it. You get a biopsy for a reason.

78
00:04:48,614 --> 00:04:51,413
And I don't understand why you wouldn't you tell me something like this.

79
00:04:51,516 --> 00:04:54,209
- Why? Take a look at yourself.
- Excuse me? What does that mean?

80
00:04:54,286 --> 00:04:57,978
It means I think that your reaction to this is completly out of scale with what is actually going on.

81
00:04:58,044 --> 00:05:00,395
- I think you're getting a little hysterical.
- Hysterical, really?

82
00:05:00,495 --> 00:05:04,582
My husband just told me he needs a biopsy and he's been keeping this information from me.

83
00:05:04,660 --> 00:05:06,164
How would you like me to react?

84
00:05:06,245 --> 00:05:09,601
You know what this is about? And I know you don't want to hear this, but with this new job of yours...

85
00:05:09,677 --> 00:05:10,838
- My job?
- One week you're busy... 

86
00:05:10,896 --> 00:05:12,985
- What has that got to do with keeping life altering events 
- And the next week you're sitting around here... 

87
00:05:13,041 --> 00:05:14,586
- ...waiting for the phone to ring 
- ...from me ?

88
00:05:14,673 --> 00:05:16,927
...and frankly, I was worried that if I told you I needed to have this little test done...

89
00:05:17,100 --> 00:05:19,006
- "Little test"?
- ...when you had too much time on your hands,

90
00:05:19,072 --> 00:05:21,877
you'd sit around here and obsess about it and drive yourself crazy.

91
00:05:22,292 --> 00:05:26,603
- Boy, was I wrong.
- What, exactly, is this biopsy for?

92
00:05:26,664 --> 00:05:28,856
You know that little mole I have my back? The one I've had forever?

93
00:05:28,938 --> 00:05:30,899
- Katkoff just thought it was finally time.
- Lay down.

94
00:05:30,972 --> 00:05:33,107
- What?
- Lay down! I want to see it!

95
00:05:33,347 --> 00:05:35,574
See? This is exactly what I'm talking about.

96
00:05:35,718 --> 00:05:38,019
When you were in school, you were so busy studying doubtful process 

97
00:05:38,105 --> 00:05:41,888
I could have been sitting in front of the Tv dead for three days and you wouldn't have noticed.

98
00:05:41,979 --> 00:05:43,755
- Australia.
- What?

99
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:45,143
Australia.

100
00:05:46,460 --> 00:05:49,563
It used to be round. Now it's shaped like Australia.

101
00:05:49,659 --> 00:05:52,404
- It itches. I scratched it. I shouldn't have.
- Don't.

102
00:05:52,973 --> 00:05:56,213
If I keep scratching it, I might get it look like the entire easten hemisphere.

103
00:05:56,494 --> 00:05:57,559
Can I get up now?

104
00:06:02,117 --> 00:06:02,909
What?

105
00:06:03,683 --> 00:06:04,574
Nothing.

106
00:06:05,973 --> 00:06:09,618
Listen to me. It's nothing, okay?

107
00:06:11,533 --> 00:06:12,403
All right.

108
00:06:12,540 --> 00:06:17,339
Nicholas Morgante is a father, is a husband, is a business man.

109
00:06:17,477 --> 00:06:21,573
He... he's a Little League coach. He's a lot of things.

110
00:06:21,679 --> 00:06:23,882
But the one thing he's not is a cop-killer.

111
00:06:23,944 --> 00:06:29,800
On the contrary, this man has enjoyed a friendly, long-standing relationship with the Phoenix Police Department

112
00:06:29,847 --> 00:06:32,918
and considered a lot of the men on the force to be close, personal friends.

113
00:06:32,986 --> 00:06:36,917
Mr. Watt, you said in a press conference yesterday that you were anticipating a speedy trial.

114
00:06:36,974 --> 00:06:40,190
- Why are you so confident?
- Well, for one thing. My client is innocent.

115
00:06:40,430 --> 00:06:44,276
For another, we know the late Detective was shot to death,

116
00:06:44,335 --> 00:06:47,223
but to date, I've yet to hear about the murder weapon.

117
00:06:47,491 --> 00:06:49,517
Has the District Attorney found the gun?

118
00:06:50,086 --> 00:06:51,480
It's not on my evidence list.

119
00:06:51,576 --> 00:06:55,861
Detective Pulaski was a highly valued and much-honored member of our police force.

120
00:06:56,395 --> 00:07:00,475
I personally had the pleasure of working with him many times over the past 15 years.

121
00:07:00,782 --> 00:07:04,622
For the record, I'm especially committed to bringing his killer to justice.

122
00:07:05,210 --> 00:07:05,821
Thank you.

123
00:07:06,793 --> 00:07:10,454
Ladies and gentlemen, no testimonial evidence has been presented which can place

124
00:07:10,495 --> 00:07:14,935
the murder weapon in Nicholas Morgante's personal possession prior to the shooting.

125
00:07:15,375 --> 00:07:18,580
No physical evidence has been presented

126
00:07:18,646 --> 00:07:23,531
which can place the murder weapon in Nicholas Morgante's personal possession prior to the shooting.

127
00:07:23,633 --> 00:07:25,684
So what are we left with, ladies and gentlemen?

128
00:07:26,684 --> 00:07:31,575
In America, is it enough for the police or the District Attorney to say,

129
00:07:32,194 --> 00:07:33,493
"I just think he did it"?

130
00:07:34,128 --> 00:07:37,759
- I think I know where it is.
- You think you know where what is ? 

131
00:07:37,831 --> 00:07:40,284
The murder weapon. The gun.

132
00:07:41,610 --> 00:07:42,541
Counselor?

133
00:07:44,256 --> 00:07:45,956
Mr. District Attorney?

134
00:07:46,838 --> 00:07:49,137
- Welcome back.
- I'm terribly sorry, Your Honor.

135
00:07:49,207 --> 00:07:52,260
And is there something you'd like to share with the rest of the court, Counsel?

136
00:07:52,673 --> 00:07:55,926
Well, Your Honor, as a matter of fact, in the interest of justice, 

137
00:07:56,020 --> 00:07:59,181
the prosecution respectfully asks the court for a recess

138
00:07:59,248 --> 00:08:02,198
due to an introduction of new evidence brought to our attention.

139
00:08:02,284 --> 00:08:05,490
Evidence that has a substantial bearing on the outcome of this case.

140
00:08:08,736 --> 00:08:11,628
In the casket, burried with detective Pulaski's body.

141
00:08:12,099 --> 00:08:14,858
- And you're sure?
- Pretty sure. Yeah.

142
00:08:16,805 --> 00:08:23,051
Allison, I'm about to go ask for a court order to disturb this man's grave, exhume his body,

143
00:08:23,137 --> 00:08:27,464
open his casket and feel around, I'd like to go to the judge with a little more than pretty sure. 


144
00:08:27,582 --> 00:08:31,945
Well I don't know what to tell you, it is a dream. You have to allow for a certain margin of error.

145
00:08:38,002 --> 00:08:41,410
Kind of inspired, isn't it? Bury the murder weapon with the victim.

146
00:08:42,692 --> 00:08:43,955
"Rest on piece"?

147
00:08:48,964 --> 00:08:50,034
I'll get a warrant.

148
00:09:05,138 --> 00:09:06,690
It's so unfair.

149
00:09:10,243 --> 00:09:15,240
Those earrings, I could tell you where you got them, when you got them, why they mean so much to you.

150
00:09:15,327 --> 00:09:20,876
but when it comes to my own husband, my own children, or anything to do with my own life.

151
00:09:21,122 --> 00:09:24,144
- Everything's a blur.
- True for all of us, I'm afraid.

152
00:09:24,711 --> 00:09:28,031
- Kind of an elegant irony, isn't it?
- You think so?

153
00:09:28,241 --> 00:09:30,846
Hey, what we don't know can't hurt us.

154
00:09:34,232 --> 00:09:38,209
But then you didn't come here to philosophize, did you? You came here for answers.

155
00:09:38,311 --> 00:09:40,068
I'm worried about my husband.

156
00:09:40,856 --> 00:09:41,833
I know.

157
00:09:42,735 --> 00:09:44,322
Do I have a reason to be?

158
00:09:45,781 --> 00:09:48,592
You know, I normally hesitate doing this kind of thing.

159
00:09:48,936 --> 00:09:52,636
People have trouble understanding when you talk to them about their futures.

160
00:09:53,231 --> 00:09:55,894
The days of our lives are a lot like the weather.

161
00:09:56,456 --> 00:10:01,392
If you look long enough and hard enough, you can absolutely find a miserable day on the horizon.

162
00:10:01,919 --> 00:10:06,010
Conversely, if you're patient enough, there's always a sunny one coming, too.

163
00:10:07,623 --> 00:10:11,837
I think the key is to focus on something fairly narrow.

164
00:10:12,011 --> 00:10:13,892
Keep the questions specific.

165
00:10:14,678 --> 00:10:16,532
Well, this is very specific.

166
00:10:16,752 --> 00:10:19,666
- Because you know I can't lie.
- I'm not asking you to lie.

167
00:10:20,976 --> 00:10:22,159
All right, then.

168
00:10:25,006 --> 00:10:29,517
Uh... there's something medical going on, right?

169
00:10:31,351 --> 00:10:32,270
Yes.

170
00:10:33,761 --> 00:10:38,575
- It's... of no consequence 
- Oh my god, really?

171
00:10:38,676 --> 00:10:42,388
This biopsy business, it's nothing. You can put it right out of your mind. 


172
00:10:42,500 --> 00:10:46,352
- So he's healthy?
- Yes, he's healthy. He's extremely healthy.

173
00:10:46,434 --> 00:10:48,998
- You're sure?
- Yes. I'm sure. I'm absolutely sure.

174
00:10:49,127 --> 00:10:50,602
So everything's okay?

175
00:10:54,007 --> 00:10:56,982
- Catherine?
- Allison, I warned you.

176
00:10:57,145 --> 00:11:00,632
- "Everything" is a very big word.
- What do you mean?

177
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:04,984
- Oh, my God. It's not one of my children?
- Don't do this to me.

178
00:11:05,450 --> 00:11:07,288
No, it's not the children.

179
00:11:08,522 --> 00:11:11,814
The... the subject was your husband.

180
00:11:11,926 --> 00:11:14,532
- But you said he was healthy.
- And he is.

181
00:11:15,121 --> 00:11:18,905
So who is it? Is somebody sick? You said you couldn't lie.

182
00:11:19,007 --> 00:11:20,743
No, nobody is sick.

183
00:11:23,641 --> 00:11:25,592
Then why are you looking that way?

184
00:11:26,386 --> 00:11:28,342
What is it you're not telling me?

185
00:11:30,117 --> 00:11:32,069
It's your marriage, dear.

186
00:11:32,621 --> 00:11:33,943
My marriage?

187
00:11:34,377 --> 00:11:36,012
What about my marriage?

188
00:11:40,086 --> 00:11:45,918
Oh... There's a... a darkness there.

189
00:11:46,158 --> 00:11:48,171
A very real darkness.

190
00:11:49,518 --> 00:11:51,475
A crisis of some kind.

191
00:11:52,508 --> 00:11:55,445
It's imminent and it's significant.

192
00:11:56,149 --> 00:11:59,870
I... I wish I could tell you more, but...

193
00:12:00,715 --> 00:12:02,021
that's all I see.

194
00:12:08,903 --> 00:12:13,469
Mom, I just felt Bridgette's toothbrush and it's completely dry. Completely.

195
00:12:13,592 --> 00:12:17,893
And then I checked that special toothpaste she made you buy her. And it hasn't even been opened.

196
00:12:17,949 --> 00:12:21,123
She's lying, Mom. My toothbrush is soaking wet. You can check it.

197
00:12:21,293 --> 00:12:24,968
That's because she just wet it. That's because she just ran it under water.

198
00:12:25,031 --> 00:12:27,754
But she didn't actually brush her teeth with it.

199
00:12:27,836 --> 00:12:30,872
That tooth brush has never seen the inside of her mouth.

200
00:12:30,995 --> 00:12:34,170
Has, too, liar! It's seen it a lot.

201
00:12:34,441 --> 00:12:35,988
Mom, are you even listening?

202
00:12:36,996 --> 00:12:39,249
Mom? Mom...!

203
00:12:41,009 --> 00:12:43,580
If you're so worried about Dad, why don't you just call him?

204
00:12:43,658 --> 00:12:45,486
I'm not worried about Dad. I'm fine.

205
00:12:45,992 --> 00:12:47,528
Did you brush your teeth?

206
00:12:48,588 --> 00:12:49,643
What?

207
00:12:50,205 --> 00:12:51,762
Okay, bedtime.

208
00:12:53,247 --> 00:12:57,511
Let's not worry. I'm sure Daddy just got tied up in traffic or his cell phone broke

209
00:12:57,604 --> 00:13:00,077
- or something came up...
- Hello, hello, hello...

210
00:13:00,180 --> 00:13:01,153
There he is.

211
00:13:02,001 --> 00:13:04,184
Well... hi.

212
00:13:04,511 --> 00:13:06,021
- Hi.
- Hi.

213
00:13:06,396 --> 00:13:07,133
Hi.

214
00:13:09,160 --> 00:13:10,194
Sorry.

215
00:13:10,753 --> 00:13:13,584
Two steps from the door and Starkey calls a meeting.

216
00:13:13,681 --> 00:13:15,422
- You didn't call.
- No. I know.

217
00:13:15,515 --> 00:13:19,058
There's no service in that wing for some reason. And you know, I tried to break away...

218
00:13:19,144 --> 00:13:22,277
And you couldn't. And you couldn't get your assistant to call?

219
00:13:27,136 --> 00:13:29,553
Girls. Come here, give me kiss good night.

220
00:13:40,776 --> 00:13:44,288
Remind me to call somebody tomorrow. There must be something wrong with that thermostat.

221
00:13:44,734 --> 00:13:46,604
It's really hot in this room.

222
00:13:46,987 --> 00:13:49,393
- I was worried, Joe.
- I said I was sorry.

223
00:13:49,487 --> 00:13:52,016
It's 9:00. How am I supposed to know you're okay?

224
00:13:52,092 --> 00:13:53,945
How do I know you're not lying dead somewhere?

225
00:13:54,031 --> 00:13:56,751
If something had happened, somebody would've called.

226
00:13:56,981 --> 00:13:59,714
If I were dead, who are we kidding, you'd be the first to know.

227
00:14:01,077 --> 00:14:03,163
Not funny. Come, eat.

228
00:14:03,940 --> 00:14:05,501
No, they already brought food in.

229
00:14:07,652 --> 00:14:09,905
So aren't you going to ask me how my biopsy went?

230
00:14:11,021 --> 00:14:12,628
How'd your biopsy go?

231
00:14:13,478 --> 00:14:14,395
Fine.

232
00:14:15,446 --> 00:14:19,346
So can I get an estimate on how long it's going to take for you to reach room temperature again?

233
00:14:19,386 --> 00:14:21,926
'Cause if there's time, I'd like to sneak in a shower here.

234
00:14:23,446 --> 00:14:25,781
A shower? You never shower at night.

